comment.editorialComment: Although the market is likely to toughen up during the course of November, there will still be some demand for most vehicles in this sector. These cars tend to represent good value for money to both trade and retail buyers alike. Over the last few years many buyers have been moving away from this sector into the heavily populated Crossover market that now exists so we are beginning to see fewer cars but there is still a ready market and if bought correctly these cars tend not to be too much of a threat in terms of stock holding costs and time to retail. Our forecast is that values will move back by around -2.5% during the course of the month.

The last two years has seen quite heavy depreciation during December for this sector compared to the four years prior to that. This we believe is a combination of higher volumes, short cycle operators de-fleeting, tactical registration activity and a general desire among most of the bigger vendors to clear the decks before the year end. Whilst volumes aren’t potentially an issue, the majority of buyers are aware that there may be some bargains to be had before during December and many will take this opportunity to increase their stock ready for the new year. With this activity comes pressure on values and the pattern that appears to be emerging is for an overall drop of around -3.0 to -3.5% during the course of the month.

January is usually a strong month for this sector and is driven by the extra demand as dealers push hard to gain traction after the traditional December lull. This sector tends to perform better than others because there is often more choice across all ages and most retail buyers can align a particular model to their needs and budget. This means that trade buyers are kept busy and find competition in the buying arena to be strong and as a consequence, values tend to get pushed up as we go through the month. Our expectation is that values will rise somewhere between 0.5% & 1.0% by the end of the month.
